LEXSense.DefinitionShort: to speak or talk, with apparent focus upon the content of what is said
to speak of a person or object by means of a proper name
to use an attribution in speaking of a person
LEXSense.Comments: It is not always possible to determine from the context whether the act involved is an initial naming of a person or simply calling a person by a particular name. Likewise in the case of attributions or titles, it is not always possible to determine whether it is a matter of giving an attribution or title to a person or simply a matter of speaking of or to a person by means of such an attribution or title. In some instances the giving of a title may be made indirect. For example, in {S:04000102300022} the statement ‘and they will call his name Emmanuel’ suggests the giving of a title, but the process is stated in terms of how people will speak of this person.

LEXSense.DefinitionShort: to mark the correspondence in the meaning of foreign expressions
LEXSense.Comments: The meaning of λέγω[d] must often be expressed in rather specific ways, for example, ‘which says in our language’ or ‘what is the same as what we say in our language.’

LEXSense.DefinitionShort: to say something in order to explain more fully the implications or intent of what has been said

LEXSubDomains.LEXSubDomain: Have an Opinion, Hold a View

LEXSense.DefinitionShort: (an idiom, literally: to speak to oneself) to think about something without communicating the content to others

Glosses.Gloss: to say to oneself (often used to introduce a direct quotation of one’s thoughts).
